{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657475/1924021201/0577.xml":{"full_text":"BUS COMPANY NET\nFOR JANUARY OFF\n\nSI,OOO Increase in Expenses\nCuts Earnings to $189.83.\n554 Employes Buy Stock.\nTho net corporate income of the\nWashington Rapid Transit Company\namourfted to $189.83 in January, as\ncompared with $1,373 for the /same\nperiod of la-st year, and with $3,429\nin December, 1923.\nComparison of tho month's figures\nwith those of a year ago show the\nloss is primarily due to increased op\nerating costs. Chassis repairs were\nstjiproxfmately SI,OOO greater, and\ngeneral and miscellaneous expenses\nrose approximately S7OO, principally\nin salaries. Total operating revenues\nduring the month amounted to\n$23,915, or about the same as last\nyear, with expenses aggregating $28.-\n63a. Deductions totaling $207 were\nmade, $l5O for taxes and $37 for li\ncenses.\nThlrly-six busses were maintained\nduring the month, carrying 354,615\neight-cent passengers. This repre\nsents an increase of 4,036 passen\ngers during the month as\nwith January, 1923, when the same\nnumber of busses were employed.\n554 Employes Buy Stock.\nA. total of 554 employes of the\nWashington Railway and Electric\nCompany and the Potomac Electric\nPower Company have purchased 1,063\nshares of railway stock via. the me\ndium offered employes of the two\ncompanies a short lime ago, it was\nreported this morning. Under the\nplan the stock can bo had on a par\ntial-payment plan as well as by cash\ntransactions.\nPurchasers of this stock are about\nequally divided between the carrier\n:cnd the lighting company, with about\n8 per cent of the number making\ncash transactions. The remainder\nelected to take advantage of the com\npany\u2019s offer on an installment basis.\nWith the disbursement of the I*4\nper cent dividend on the common and\npreferred stock of tho company,\nwhich will be declared on February\n19 and paid .March 10. the railway\ncompany will round out its first year\nof a 5 per cent payment on the com\nmon stock. This rdte has been dis\nbursed on the preferred forborne time.\nRICE SALES ADVANCE\nAT SURPRISING RATE\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW ORLEANS, February 12.\u2014The\nstatement of the Associated Rice Mills\nissued this week showed a distribu\ntion of about 1,250,000 bags of rice\nduring January. This was nearly a\nquarter of a million bushels larger\nthan expected. Millers are very firm\nIn their views because of the dimin\nishing supply anil the probability of\nan acute situation before the next\ncrop becomes available. The market\nhas been dull recently, owing to the\napparent unwillingness of the trade\nto pay the high prices. Mills are\nbow demanding 4% to 5 cents a_ pound\nfor fancy blue rose and 514 to 514 fur\nextra fancy.\nBUILDING SLOW IN JAPAN.\nCommerce Department Expert Re\nports on Conditions.\nPHILADELPHIA, February 12.\nExtent of. the Japanese earthquake\ndamage is not yet known, HallocK A.\nButts, assistant chief, far eastern di\nvision, bureau of foreign and domes\ntic commerce, told the Export Club\nat a luncheon here. Officially the es\ntimate is put in round figures at\n$7,000,000,000 to $10,000,000,000. but\nmaterial and merchandise loss will\nprobably be less than this, as labor\ncost is figured in as the greater por\ntion. 3lr. Butts has just returned\nfrom a three-year stay in Japan.\nThe payment of some $980,000,000 in\ninsurance to the big companies suf\nfering the greatest losses is the prob\nlem that is holding up the renewal of\nactivity and reconstruction, Mr. Butts\nsaid. So far, Yokohama has done\nnothing toward restoration of her\nbusiness facilities. No permanent\nbuildings have been started, nor have\nship channels and wharves been re\npaired. A number of American firms\nhave set up steel hangars, similar to\nthose used Tor airplane housing, as\ntemporary warehouses and offices.\nIndications, however, point toward\nthe eventual restoration of Yokohama\nas a seaport, as the dredging of a\nchannel to Tokio would be too ex\npensive and the geographical location\nunadaptud to good distribution of\ngoods throughout the orient.\nCURB BODY ELECTS.\nNEW YORK, February 13.\u2014Six\nmembers for the board of governors\nof tho New York Curb Market Asso\nciation were elected yesterday. John\nColeman, defeated by John J. Man-\nTram, was the only unsuccessful can\ndidate. Those elected are HerbeH T.\nHodge, Mortimer Landsberg, John J.\nMaoTrum, Norton F. Stern, D. E.\nSpencer and George C. Winchell.\nThey will serve for three years.\nGASOLINE SALES DROP.\nCHICAGO, February 12 (Special).\nGasoline prices havo held up in this\nterritory, although weather condi\ntions have greatly lowered sales.\nKero sine and distillate, however, have\naold in unusuaJ quantities at firm\nprices.\nBERLIN BANK REPORT.\nBERLIN, February 22. \u2014The statc\nment of the Bank of Germany as of\nJanuary 31 shows a decrease of 103,-\n085,000 marks in coin and bullion.\nGold holdings remained unchanged at\n467,031,000.\nWHEAT SALES CONFIRMED.\nPORTLAND. Ore.. February 12\n(Special).\u2014Sale of three cargoes of\nwheat from Pacific northwest ports\nto the United Kingdom has been con\nfirmed here, but the prices named arc\nsaid to bo barely sufficient to pay re\nplacement costs. Two of the cargoes\nwore sold by Portland exporters and\none by a Puget so.und interest.\nN. Y. Stock and Bond\nAverages.\nMonday, February 11,\nSTOCKS.\nTotal stock sales, 663,000\n\u201cshares.\nTwenty industrials averaged\n101.09; net'loss, .15.\nHigh. 1924, 101.24; low, 94.88.\nTwenty railroads averaged\n84.91: net gain. .30.\nHigh, 1934, 86.90; low, 82.1T4.\nBONDS.\nTotal bond sales (par value).\n$9,000,000.\nTen first grade rails averaged\n86.05; net loss. .13.\nTen secondary rails averaged\n84.08; net loss. .09.\nTen public utilities averaged\n86.56; net loss, .12.\nTan industrials averaged\n98.98; net lose, .12.\nCombined average, 87.68; net\nloss. .11.\nCombined average month ago,\ntT.Tf; year ago, 88.81.\nFISANCIAE.\nPROSPERITY INCREASING\nGENERALLY, SAYS BARNES\nArea of Distress Limited and Im\nprovement Likely There, Declares\nCommerce Chamber Head.\nBy the Associated Pros*.\nCHICAGO. February 12. \u2014Manufac-\nturing and general business seems to\nbe advancing throughout the nation,\nwith some measure of earnings on\nthe right side, according to Julius H.\nBarnes, president of the Chamber of\nCommerce bf tho United States.\nTho area of distress centers in cer\ntain few industries, cattle raising,\ncopper mining and single-crop grain\nraising, he said. The cattle industry\nshows signs of recovery, with south\nwestern ranges in promising condi\ntion; copper mining needs the return\nto stable coi di lions-Hi Europe to re\nstore it to full activity, and diversified\nfarming is replacing single-crop grain\nraising, according to his report.\n\u201cCotton and dairy farming are cn- I\njoying a faip measure sos actual pros- I\nporlty, he said. \u201cThe oil industry\nseems to have passed its worst stage 1\nof depressing overproduction and is I\non the up-grade.\u201d\nThe government should have no\nopinion on prices, but should devote\nits energy to maintaining the fair\nand uninfluenced field in which nat\nural Influences make prices and work\nout the question of any disparities,\nUr. Barnes declared.\nGrain, Produce and\nLive Slock\nLOCAL WHOLESALE MARKET.\nCold weather along the east coast\nof Florida, tho thermometer register\ning slightly above the freezing point,\nhas lessened supplies of peas, string\nbeans and eggplant and caused in\ncreased prices. Eggplants have been\nespecially scarce the past days.\nThere has been a change in (he tem\nperature, however, and increased sup\nplies are expected in tho near future.\nBecause of the frozen condition of\nthe ground in the vicinity of Nor\nfolf, Va., local dealers have hail to\ncall upon gVowers in Texas for sup\nplies of spinach. Increased receipts\nlowered prices. One hundred and fif\nty barrels of kale was received from\nNorfolf this morning and cheaper\nprices rule.\nReceipts of potatoes from Michigan\nand New York have been ample to\nsupply the local trade at prices that\ndealers consider reasonable. There\nare plenty of turnips .on hand, but\ntheir quality is not so good because\nof the late season. Plentiful supplies\nof tomatoes have been received from\nFlorida and small shipments of the\nvegetable have been received from\nCuba.\nEggs\u2014Strictly fresh, selected, can\ndied, per dozen, *44a45; average\u2019 re\nceipts, 40; storage. 28a30.\nLive poultry\u2014Hoos'ers. per lb., 17;\nturkeys, per lb., 25a30; spring chick\nens. per lb., 30-31; keats, young, each,\n60a70; fowls, per lb., 26.\nDressed poultry Fresh killed\nspring chickens, per lb., 32a35;\nroasters, per lb.. 32a33; hens, per\nlb., 27; turkeys, per lb., 28a32; keats,\nyoung, each, 80a85; roosters, per lb.,\n20.\nLive stock\u2014Calves, choice, per lb.,\n14; medium, per lb., 12a13; thin, per\nlb., SalO. Lambs, spring, per lb., 13.\nLive pigs, 3.00a5.00 each; live hogs,\nper lb., 7=4.\n_ Creen fruits\u2014Apples, per basket.\naOaS.OO; box, 1.50a3.00; per barrel, 2.00\na6.00. California oranges, per crate.\n3.50a4.50; Florida, 3.00a4.0u. Lemons,\nPer box, 3.50a4.00. Grapefruit, 3.00a\n3.73. Cranberries, 4.50a5.50 per one\nhalf barrel.\nVegetables\u2014Potatoes, nearby, per\nbarrel. No. 1, 2.50a3.00; No. B, 1.50a\n-.00. Potatoes, round, per bag. 2.75a\n3.25; sweet potatoes. 5.00a7.00 per bar\nrel. Southern lettuce, per crate, 1.50a i\n3.00; Iceberg. 3.00a3.25. Cabbage, I\nnorthern, 2.0t)a2.50 per 100 lbs.; Flor- I\nIda, 2.00a2.25 basket: nearby, 1.00a1.50 I\nbarrel. Tomatoes, Florida, 3.00a4.50. i\nBeans, southern, per basket, 3.50a5.50.\nPeas, per basket, 4.00a8.00. Celery.\nFlorida, 2.75a3.00. Squash, 5.00a4.00. i\nPeppers, per crate, Florida, 2.50a4.00.\nEggplant, 4.00a5.00. Kale, per barrel,\n1.75a2.00. Spinach, per barrel, 4.50a\n5.00; Texas. per basket. 2.00a2.50.\nSouthern cucumbers, per bushel, 5.00\naS.OO. Carrots. 100-lb. sack, 3.00a3.25.\nBrussels sprouts, 25a30. Florida lima\nbeans. 4.00a5.00.\nGRAIN AND PROVISIONS.\nBALTIMORE. Md., February' 12 j\n(Special).\u2014Potatoes, white, 100 lbs.,\n90a2.00; 160 lbs.. 1.50a3.00; sweets and\nyams, bbl., 2.00a6.50; bu., 1.00a2 75-\nbeets, 100, 4.00a6.00; beans, bu., 3.30a\n5.00; broccoli and kale, bu., 25a30:\nbrussels sprouts, qt\u201e 25a30; cabbage,\n100, 3.00a6.00; savoy, bu., 40a50; car-\nrots, 100. 4.00a6.00; cauliflower, crate,\n2.50a2.75; celery, crate, 1.75a2.50; cu- i\ncumbers, crate, S.OOaS.OO; eggplants, I\nbu.. 3.00a5.00; lettuce, basket. 1.50a I\n2.d0; onions, 100 lbs., 1.50a2.75; par- j\nsnips, basket, 50a60; peas, hampetr,\n6.00a6.50; peppers, crate, 2.50a4.00;\nspinach, bu., 1.70a2.00; squash, crate,\n4.00a5.00; tomatoes, crate, 1.50a3.25;\nturnips, bu., 35a40.\nApples, packed, bbl., 2.00a5.00; bo:,\n50a1.50; box apples. 1.75a2.25; grape\nfruit, box, 1.75&3.00; oranges, box,\n2.23a3.75; pineapples, crate, 3.50a4.00;\nstrawberries, qt,, 35a55.\nDAIRY PRODUCTS.\nBALTIMORE, Md., February 12\n(Special).\u2014Live poultry: Turkeys,\npound, 18a30; young chickens, 20a35;\nleghorns, 20a25; old hens, 18a24; leg\nhorns, 18a20; old roosters, 14a15;\nducks, 22a30; geese, 17a22; pigeons,\npair, 30; guinea fowl, each, 30a60.\nDressed poultry\u2014Turkeys, pound,\n18a31; chickens, 20a30; ducks, 28a30;\nold roosters, 16; geese, 18a22; capons,\n28a3a.\nEggs, loss off native and nearby\nfirsts, dozen, 43; southern, 42.\nButter, creamery good to fancy,\npound, 48a53; prints, 53a55; nearby\ncreamery, 42a46; ladles, 30a32; rolls,\n26a30; storepacked, 26a27; dairy\nprints, 26a28; process butter, 39.\nNo grain quotations, market closed.\nDRUG PRICES DECLINE.\nBetter Demand for General List of\nMaterials.\nNEW YORK,*. February 12.\u2014Lead\ning developments in the drug and\nfine chemical market last week, ac\ncording to \u201cThe Oil, Paint and Drug\nReporter\u201d In Its current Issue, were\nthe sharp declines In potash iodine,\nresubllmed iodine, calomel, corrosive\nsublimate and santonin. The down\nward revisions came as the result of\nsharp competition between domestic\nfactors and importers. Menthol\neased off slightly and closed at lower\nprices.\nBetter demand for the general list\nof materials was reported, and gave\nrise to better feeling.in the trade.\nLIVERPOOL COTTON.\nLIVERPOOL, February 12.\u2014Cotton\n\u2014Spot in fair demand; prices easier\nGood middling, 19.82; fully middling!\n19.32; middling, 18.82; low middling\n17.82; good ordinary, 16.82; ordinary.\n16.33. Sales, 8,000 bales, including\n5,900 American. Receipts, 9,000 bales,\nno American. Futures closed steady\nFebruary, 19.03; March, 19.12; May\u2019\n19.13; July, 18.65; September, 17 02\nOctober, 16.44; December, 16.01; Jan\nuary, 15.90.\nWILL SPEND $100,000,000.\nST. LOUIS, February j 2 (Special)\nThe Union Electric Light and Power\nCompany announces that in the next\nit will spend $100,000,000 in\nthe St. Louis district in adding to\nfacilities, including the Cahokia plant,\nwhich, when completed, will cost\n$35,000,000.\nPRUNE DEMAND-PICKS UP.\nSEATTLE. February 12 (Special).\u2014\nResumption of buying of Washington\nml Oregon prunes by New York and\nther Atlantic cities is reported hera\n'or ty thousand boxes of prunes are\nJ o be shipped from north Pacific ports\nI this month.\n\ns\nTHE EVENING ST'AR, WASHINGTON, D. C, TUESDAY, FEBRUARY 12, 1924.\nSLIGHT RISE LIKELY\nIN AUIO PRICES\nI\nOther Firms May Follow Step\nby Oldsmoblle \u2014Tire Trade\n9 1\nVery Much Confused.\np\nBY J. C. HOYLE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, February 12.\u2014The in\ncreases just named by the Olds Motor\nWorks, ranging from S3O to $46 in\nthe prices of its automobile models,\nI did not come unexpectedly to the au-\nItomobilc trade. Similar advances in\ni other makes are known to be contem\nj plated. The advances, however, are\nj expected to be slight, and will be im\nposed to cover the cost of additional\nrefinements offered this year, such as\nfour-wheel brakes and balloon tires.\nSo many makers have adopted\nchanges in equipment that men close\nto the automobile situation here be\nlieve the Olds move will bo welcomed\nby the trade. N t\nNew Prim Old.mobile*.\nThe price boosts on Oldsmoblles in\ncreased the price of the touring car\nfrom <750 to $795 f.o.b. Lansing. The\nnew price of the roadster is\nthe coupe $1,075 and of the sedan\n$1,135 The volume of sales so far\nthis year seem to have had compara\ntively little to do with the upward\nprice tendency. The Olds works are\na part of the General Motors Corpora\ntion, and that company sold more\nthan 66.0<i0 cars of their various types\nin January.\nAs to the trend of sales for the\ntrade in general, nothing is more sig\nnificant than the results of the Twin\nCities automobile show, which ended\nlast week. The dealers and buyers\nwho were to this exhibition\ncovered the territory supposed to\nhave been most severely stricken by\nagricultural depression. Yet the\nwinter and spring sales which were\ndeveloped by this show are fixed by\nofficials at $20,0*0,000, on a basis of\nretail orders and agency contracts.\nThis total includes $2,000,000 worth\nof sales actually made on the show\nfloor. The remainder is covered by\norders given by northwestern deal\ners.\nProduction at High Hate.\nTotal production of cars and trucks\nin January totaled 343.000, an Increase\nof 41 per cent over January, 1923.\nThere is every indication this figure\nwill rise well above 350,000 this\nmonth. The number, of workers em\nployed in the Detroit factories is at a\nrecord level.\nThere .still exists a feeling of un\ncertainty in regard to the tiro situa\ntion. Dealers have be\u00a3n waiting to\nsee just how the public would take\nto baloon tires before stocking heav\nily. They have feared ta lay in\nheavy supplies of the old high-pres\nsure tires for fear there would be\na widespread trend tpward the bal\nloons, and have been equally afraid\nto stock the low-pressure type for\nfear owners would not go to the\nexpense of changing tires all around\nwhen it came time for replacements.\nTire Situation Uncertain.\nThe announcement -just made by\nmakers, however, that car owners\nwill not have to discard their present\n(wheels and rims, to which the first\nballoon could .not be attached, has\nhad an Immediate and widespread\neffect. Tire makers now have made j\nit possible to equip present wheels\nwith balloon tires. Two large manu\nfacturers now are offering two sets\nof these tires as standard, one for\nJ use with the regular wheels and one\nfor the special wheels being placed\njon the new cars.\nUnder this system, tho Ford, Chev\ni rolet and Overland size wheel\u20143ox\nI 3*4 \u2014will take a balloon size 31x4\n4-10 inches, while the ordinary 33x\nI 4\u20184-inch wheel will take a 34x5 77-\n100-inch low-pressure tire.\nCrude Rubber Salee luereuae.\nSales of crude rubber have increas\ned this month, according to Fred B.\nPeterson, a large dealer here. The\namount of rubber in the old and new\ntypos does not materially differ, he\nexplained today, but factories are\nI busy turning out tires of both types.\nTho activity' of the automobile\nmanufacturers Is having a stimulat\ning effect on the steel industry, and\noperations in the Youngstown, Sharon\nand Valley district were increased\nthis week. However, many steel men\nI will feel far easier when the wage\nagreement now under consideration\nj by the operators and mine workers of\nthe central competitive field is \u00abet\nj lied, in spite of the conciliatory atti\ntude shown by each side at the open\ning meetings.\nHARDWARE SALES GOOD.\nBope, Ash Sifters, Tacks and Cop\nper Bivete (Are Higher.\nNEW YORK, February 12.\u2014Hard\nware Age, in Its summary of the\nhardware markets, will say tomor\nrow:\n\"Current sales in practically all of\nthe \u2022major hardware markets\nthroughout the country are active;\nprice tendencies are stiffening slight\nly. and future business booked by\nI jobbers is said to bo substantially\nlarger than it was at this time last\nyear.\n\u201cAlthough the open winter has re\ntarded the sale of snow and ice bools\nIn many sections, this is said to have\nbeen offset to a large extent by in\ncreased demands for builders\u2019 hard\nware, carpenters\u2019 and mechanics\u2019\ntools and automobile accessories.\n\"Jobbers in some sections believe\nthat prices in several lines are likely\nto advance in the near future because\nof the increased demand, the absence\nof any surplus stocks and the ap\nparent tendency on tho part of re\ntailers to place larger orders.\n\u201cAmong the important advances of\nthe week announced by jobbers were:\nManila ropo advanced 2 cents per\npound base; tacks have been ad\nvanced approximately 10 per cent;\nash sifters and stove board ad\nvanced 10 per cent and copper rivets\nand burrs were reduced about 10\nper cent. _\nHave Yoa Been Staagr Yet?\nSome men have to get stung good\nand bard before they learn to be cau\ntious In making investments. Be\nfore you Invest \u2014Investigate!\nBUSINESS IS RUSHING\nIN PITTSBURGH AREA\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nPITTSBURGH, February 12.\u2014Pitts\nburgh business and industrial in\nterests are highly optimistic as to\nthe immediate, outlook. This Is due\npartly to tbe imprefeement displayed\nin the steel market and partly be\ncause general business are\nshaping up so as to encourage more\nextensive buying. Tbe 860.000,000 In-\nI dustrial pay roll for this district in\nthe last two weeks has exceeded-even\nthat of the pre-Christmas period.\nThe crude oil market is very firm\nand coal is steady. Bituminous in\nterests are encouraged at the decision\nof the western Pennsylvania opera\ntors to sit in the wage agreement dis\ncussions at Jacksonville. Coke is\nquiet, with current demand below pro\nduction. The weather has favored\nconstruction work and building\nmaterials and hardware are in ex\ncellent demand.\nDIVIDENDS DECLARED.\nMONTREAL, February 12.\u2014The\nboard of directors of tbe Canadian\nPacific Railway Company has declared\na dividend of 2 per cent on the pre\nferred stock for the half year ended\nDecember 31 and a dividend of 2*\u00a3\nper cent on tbe common stock for the\nquarter ended December 81. Beth\ndividends are payable April 1 to\nstockholders of record February 29.\nf\nWATER COSTS PENNSY\n$4,000,000 PER YEAR\nPHILADELPHIA. February 12.\u20141 t\ncost the Pennsylvania railroad sys\ntem nearly $4,000,000 for water for its\nlocomotives and shops last year. This\ni was spent on. water for boiler usee and\nmostly, in this state. An officer of the\ncompany said the human boiler or\nstomach could stand water that would\nsoon ruin the tubes of>a locomotive\nboiler. \u201cIt is not generally known,\"\nho asserted, \"but it is true, if A. J.\nCassatt, former president, had not\nseen far ahead and made provisibns\nto secure an unadulterated water sup\nply, the company would be unable to\noperate Its system in Pennsylvania.**\nAn officer .of the company says:\n\u201cOne-third of the state is underlaid\nwith coal, and the seepage from the\nmine is sulphur water, which is rank\npoison to boilers, so we must secure\ntil adequate supply of the pure arti\ncle. We are looking to the future\nand our locomotives are given noth\ning that will take the lining off their\nboilers. The operation of the railroad\nrequires large quantities of water of\na high degree of purity. Such waters\nmust contain only a small amount of\nalkali, no suspended matter and-only\na small quantity of those substances\nwhich form hard scales in steam\nboilers.*\u2019\nBIG BUILDING YEAR\nIS NOW ASSURED\nRailroads and Factories Hare Ex\ntensive Plants for Costly\nExpansion.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star,\nNEW YORK, February 12.\u2014The key\nto the business outlook Is to be found\nthis yea t in building operations. Keep\nyour eye on the builders Is the advice\nof the National City Bank.\nThis means not merely the builders\nof houses, but the builders of railroads\nand industrial plants in particular.\nThe housing shortage is still with\nus. Everybody knows that. Unless\nprices advance beyond the point of\nreason, house-building must go on.\nPrices are not likely to do this. The\nexperience of 1919 and 1920 will save\nus from that. What Is probably more\ninteresting is the indication that rail\nread building will continue upon an\nactive scale, and that there will be\na resumption of Industrial construc\ntion. Bast year in a total of nearly\n$6,000,000,000 there was but $750,000,-\n000 put into factories. In this very\nmaterial and highly industrial coun\ntry more money was spent building\nchurches than factories and nearly\ntwice as much building schools.\nThe reason\u2014industry has been\nslowly catching up with the over\ndevelopment of the war. Billions of\ndollars were put into factory con\nstruct which was vacated when the\npeace slowed things down. The same\nthing has been true of machine tools.\nEnough tools were made to afford the\ncountry a tremendous surplus. Now\nwe are catching up with that surplus\nin tools and factory buildings. This\nyear there is a promise of greater In\ndustrial construction. The steel in\ndustry furnishes an index. It was\ngenerally believed that this business\nhad been expanded during the war to\na point which would preclude further\nbuilding, for another ten years. Yet\na .number of leading companies arc\nplanning extensions, and the United\nStates Steel Corporation lias plans\nfor $15,000,000 of capital expenditures\nthis year.\nBUSINESS TOPICS.\nUtilities Commission Plans Appeal\nto Congress.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nTOPEKA, Kan., February 12. \u2014The\nKansas Public Utilities Commission\nhas appealed to Congress for aid In\nhaving the telephone companies re\nmoved from jurisdiction of the In\nterstate Commerce Commltvsion so far\naa depreciation charges are con\nearned.\nCHICAGO. February I!.\u2014Figures\njust compiled show that furniture\nmerchants here carried 2.370.066 lines\nof advertising in Chicago newspapers\nin 1923. This was an increare over\n1923 and sales were larger during\nthe last year than for a number of\nseasons.\nLUMBER DEMAND KEEN.\nFirst Week iu February Keeps In\ndustry Optimistic.\nNEW YORK, February 12. \u2014Lum-\nber demand, which during January\ndeveloped strongly and reached high\nlevels, remained keen during the first\nweek of February, says the Ameri\ncan Lumberman, Chicago. The out\nlook haa brightened constantly as\nthe year has progressed, and high op\ntimism pervades the industry. Not\nonly are general Industrial prospects\nvery good, but preparations are clear\nly being made for ope of the biggest\nbuilding years In the country's his\ntory,\nNET FSOFITS HIGHER.\nNEW YORK. February 12.\u2014The\nreport of Cluett, Peabody Co., Inc.,\nfor the year ended December 31 last\nshowed net profits of $3,129,666 after\nall charges and taxes, equivalent\nafter preferred dividends to $14.15 a\nshare earned on the $18,000,000 com\nmon stock outstanding. This com\npared with $2,751,441, or $12.01 a\nshare earned the preceding year.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK GOOD.\nBALTIMORE. February 12 (Spe\ncial). \u2014The general outlook for busi\nness 'in Baltimore for 1924 is most\nencouraging, according to the month\nly industrial report of A. S. Golds\nborough, secretary of the Merchants\nand Manufacturers\u2019 Association, just\nissued. V\nThe only fly In the ointment, ac\ncording to the report. Is the fear of\n\u201cexcessive demands for wage in\ncreases\u2019* in building trades.\nEX-DIVIDEND TABLE.\nFebruary _l4 _\nHousehold Predact*.\nIngeruoll-lUnd, q..\nNational Blacuit pf., 14*%\nFebruary 15\u2014\nBrooklyn City. It. 8., q -5\nConsolidated daar pf., l-7j\u00bb\nGooden a Co. pf..\nCuba Co., q... x\nDeere A Co. pf., q.\nDuqueane Light pL,q. l-*5\nFederal Light Traction pf., 4\nGeneral Asphalt pf., q IH%\nInland Steel,\nLiggett Myers Tob., 8%\nLiggett ft Myera com. B, 4 3%\nLima Locomotive,\nManatl Sugar, q LJS\nnJSSIm d&. Wm m vs.:\nn. I: c. IV. u k bV V.\u2019ih|\nPure Oil,\nStandard Oil of Indiana, q............. .ffi%\nSchulte BetaU Stores (In pfd. stock).. 2.00\nSouthern Pipe Line, q 2;\u00ae\u00ae\nUnion Tank Car pf.. q\nUnited Druga, Lop\nUnited Drug 3d pf\u201e 4 IH%\nAlaharaa^Great South, pf.. H.....,..,\nAmerican Metal*\nBart Sehnffher ft Marx, 4\nHartman Coro., q. too\nStandard Miffing, 1%%\nStandard Milling pf.. 4... IH%\nTimken Holler Bearing, q 75\nTimken Boiler Bearing, eat .26\nWright Aeronautical, q .20\nDIVIDENDS.\nv Pay- Stock of\nOMipaay. Pr. Bate. able. Becord.\nFans. Players-Laaky. Q $2 Apr. 1 Mch. 13\nMcCrary Stores \"A\u201d Q 1% Mch. 1 Feb. 20\nMcOrenr Stores \u201cA\u201dEx *5% Mch. 1 Feb. 20\nMcCrary Stores Q 1 Mch. 1 Feb,So\nMcCrary Stores \u201cB\u201dEx *5% Mch. 1 Feb. 20\nSaco-LowsU 2d pf.. Q 1%% Mch. 1 Feb. 20\n\u2018Payable in stock. _\n\nThe number of men bow employed in\nthe coal mines of Great Britain is 1,184,-\nPROMISES SSOO.QOQ 1\nFOR NEEDY BANKS;\nI\n8\nNational City Bank Adds, to S\n1 2\nFund Started by Morgan.\nLatest Relief Steps.\n______ n\nt\nBy the Associated Frees. 1\nNEW YORK. February 12.\u2014The\nNational City Bank has added a sub- e\nscriptlon of $500,000 to the Service 0\nCorporation, the organization being\nformed with $10,000,000 capital to as- 1\nslst banks in the northwest.\nJohn McHugh, the New York bank- 1\ning member of the committee named\nin Washington a week ago to draft\nrelief measures, said other large\nNew York financial institutions have\nagreed to subscribe large amounts\nproviding leading banks and indus\ntries in other parts of the country do I\nlikewise.\nMr. McHugh said at least half of the\n$10,000,000 capital was expected to\ncome from the large western financial,\ntransportation and industrial inter\nests. Completion of the Service Cor\nporation's organization will be under\ntaken in Chicago Thursday.\nJ. P. Morgan Co. made a $500,000\ncontingent subscription Saturday,\nCOTTON CONTROL IDEA]\nPROVES FAILURE\nAttempt to Fonn Board Is Aban\ndoned After Long Confer\nences in England.\nBy the Associated Press.\nMANCHESTER, England, February\n12-\u2014The attempt to form a cotton\ncontrol board has ended unsuccess\nfully. The decision was reached after\na long series of conferences, the last\nof which took place yesterday, that\nowing to diversity of interests it was\nimpracticable to devise a plan which\nwould meet with the approval of all\nthe interests concerned. Therefore\nthe entire project was abandoned.\nA dispatch from Manchester Jan\nuary 25 said that at a meeting of\nemployers engaged In the spinning\nand manufacturing of American cot\nton approval had been given to a\nplan for the appointment of a board\nof control for ,-the cotton industry.\nThe plan was said to embrace regu\nlation of production and the imposi\ntion of levies on mills, payable both\nby employers and workers. The\namount secured through tho levies\nwas to be applied to tho payment of\nworkers made idle through stagnant\ntrade.\nLIVE STOCK RECEIPTS. j\nBALTIMORE, February 12.\u2014Live\nstock receipts here yesterday were; J\nCattle \u2014Rereiptsf 625 head; 76 car- j\nloads for the week; with light re- I\nceipts, market active and stronger:\n25 higher on spot, mostly on cows and j\nbetter grade steers. Steers \u2014Choice,\n9.25a9.75; good butcher. 5.25a8.75; me-\ndlum, 7.25a8.00; common, 5.5ua6.5u. 1\nHeifers \u2014Choice, 7.00a7.75; fair to\ngood, 6.06a6.75; .common to medium 1\n3.50a5.25. Bulls \u2014Choice, 5.75a6.25; fair\nto good, 4.25a5.00; common to medium,\n3.25a4.00. Cows \u2014-Choice, 5.25a5.75;\nfair to good, 4 25a4.75; common to j\nmedium, 1.75a3.75.\nSheep and lambs\u2014Receipts, 1,200\nhead; light supply: market steady;\nsheep. 3.00a8.00; lambs, 8.00a15.00.\nHogs\u2014Receipts, 6.500 head; good\nsupply; market lower; flights, 7.80;\nheavy, 8.05; medium, 8.05; pigs, 0.90; f\nlight pigs. 6.25; roughs, 4.00a6.25.\nCalves\u2014Receipts, 550 head; good\nsupply; market steady; calves, 5.50a\n14.00.\nj\nCOAL EXPORTS INCREASE.\nBALTIMORE. February 12 (Spe-\ncial). \u2014Coal exports through the port\nof Baltimore increased heavily dur-\ning January over the total for Janu- j\nary, 1923. During the past month the\naggregate was 55,264 tons; for the 1\ncorresponding period last year it was\n4,119 tons. One shipment of 3,491\ntons of coke also went out.\nCOTTONSEED OIL DROPS.\nNEW YORK, February 13.\u2014Cotton- I\nseed oil made new lows for the move- J\nmeat yesterday under liquidation by\ncotton houses and scattered local sell\ning, encouraged by the decline in lard\nand cotton, easier crude and slow cash\ndemand generally. Closing bids were\nnear the lowest and showed net\nlosses of 13 to 19 points. Sales, 26.-\n300 barrels. Prime crude. 8.62% bid;\nprime summer yellow spot, 9.75 bid;\nMarch closed 10.17 bid; May, 10.56;\nJuly, 10.75, all bid.\nCOMMODITY NEWS\nWIRED STAR FROM j\nENTIRE COUNTRY j\ni\nFoftT WORTH. February 12.\u2014Wheat j\nis beginning to show up green in the\nplains counties, after a series of hard\nfreezes and much snow.\nKANSAS CITY. February 12.\u2014A car\nload of Hereford bulls assembled at\ntho stock yards from Missouri and Texas\nherds is on its way to the ranch of the\nGreene Cananea Cattle Company in old 1\nMexido to improve the Mexican strain, j\nBOISE, Idaho. February 12.\u2014Large\npooled lots of Idaho and eastern Oregon\nwool of last year's clip are being closed\nout at prices ranging from 42 to 44\ncents in the grease.\nBOSTON, February 12.\u2014Cold weather\nhas Interfered with shipments of eggs\nfrom the west and prices here have\nadvanced 3to 5 cents a dozen. Stocks 1\nof storage eggs have declined nearly I\n20,000 cases in the last week and it is\nfeared they will not last the month out.\nDANVILLE. Va., February 12.\u2014To\nbacco sold here in January totaled\n5,722,174 pounds. The average price -was\n$23.94. The season\u2019s total is more than\n30,671,918 pounds, sold for more than 1\n$7,000,000. j\nATLANTA. February 12.\u2014Ctftidy man-\nufacturdra and jobbers have experi\nenced a decided increase in business\nlately, but they are at a loss to account\nfor it.\nCLEVELAND, February 12.\u2014Increas-\ned buying by farmers has stimulated\nproduction of bolts and nuts. Orders\ntaken in recent months for farm im\nplements have exceed those for the\nlast three years, according to the pres\nident of the Lake Erie Bolt and Nut\nCompany. Heavy buying by railroads\nalso is reported. 1\nPITTSBURGH. February 12.\u2014Sea\nsonal, buying by western interests has\nincreased operations among wire mills\nin this district. Average operations\nare In excess of 75 per cent of capacity.\nPrices are very firm.\nPHILADELPHIA, February 12.\u2014Two\ncarloads of steel wire which will be\nmade into cables for the new Delaware\nRiver bridge have arrived here. Each\nwire is 4-5 inch in diameter and 17,000 j\nwill be used in each cable.\nSAN FRANCISCO. February 12.\u2014The I\nErnest Wilson Company, confectioners,\nwith branches here, at Fresno. San\nJose, Stockton and Palo Alto, stated\ntoday that the mechanical process for\ndipping* raisins la chocolate has pro\ngressed to such a stage that ft is now\npossible to offer chocolate-dipped raisins\nfive-cent various.\nBIG 1924 BUSINESS\nPREDICTED BY FORD\nBOSTON. February 12.\u2014Henry Ford,\nin an interview published here, is quoted\nas saying be could see nothing but big\nbusiness for 1924.\n\u201cWe are planning for a 15 per cent\nto 20 per cent increase in output of\nFord cars; Lincolns and tractors,\u201d he\nsaid. \u201cAgainst-output of these exceed\ning 2,200,000 in 1923, I am confident we\nwill manufacture between 2,500.000 and\n3,600,000 in 1924. *niis will include all\nour plants in Detroit, England and Can\nada.\n\u201cSuch has been the pressure for trans\nportation for our products from our New\nYork plant to New England that we are\nnow shipping by our own boats and by\nthe same method from Albany to New\nYork. *We have In mind decentralizing\nmanufacturing activities somewhat. We\nhave enough men in Detroit now. We\nemploy there between 115,000 and 120,-\n000. We have a $5,000,000 plant in Ire\nland and the workers there are a fine\nbody of men.\n\u201cWe have purchased Johanseen Gauge\nCompany of Sweden, which also has a\nbig plant in Poughkeepsie. It turns out\ninstruments that measure correctly to\na millionth of an inch. Mr. Johansson\nis with our organization.\u201d\nEQUITABLE\nCo-Operative Building\nAssociation\nOrganized 1879\n44th TEAR COMPLETED\nA Meta 04,756,170.62\nSurpiwa 01.348,390.\u2122\nAccomplishes Most\nSystematic sating la the most\neff-ctite meant of accumulating\nmoney. Joint the Equitable and sars\nwith best results.\nSubscription for (he\n86th Issue of Stock\nBeing Received\nShares, $2.50 Per Month\nEQUITABLE BUILDING\n915 F St N.W.\nJOHN JOT EDSON. President\nFRA MR P. REBSIDB, Bee*y.\nWILL BUY\nALL ISSUES\nGERMAN\nBONDS\nMain 2867\n435 Star Bkfg.\n18*\nj j\nPorto Rico\nCoupon\n5% Gold Bonds\nDue 1944-49\u2014Opt. 1943\nExempt from all Federal,\nState and Local Taxation\nPrice 106 interest\nyielding better than\n4.50%\ntc 1943 and thereafter\nThe National City Company\nWashington\n741 15th St. N.W.\nTelephone Main 3176\nBIG 1924 BUSINESS\nA\nF ailnre to IVlake\na 'W ill\nHappens AgakL and Again I\n_\nIf you want to avoid such a mistake and prepare for\nthe future of your family, place your estate in the hands of\nthis Company, and have your Will drawn naming us as\nExecutor and Trustee of Your Estate. t\nThe service we render, extending over thirty-five years,\nin administering Wills and managing estates is well known.\ny\nConsult any of the officers in our Trust Department\nregarding our Trust Service.\nAmerican security\nAND TRUST C OMPANY I\n15th mid Penna. Ave.\nCapital, Surplus and Undivided Profits s\nOver $6,000,000.00.\nI\nBRANCHES\nCentral: 7th Mass. Ave. N.W.\nNortheast: Bth H Sts. N.E.\nSouthwest 436 7th St. S.W